Nonmetric multidimentional scaling - Anderson et al 2011

Laurence Dumouchel

April 11, 2015

Anderson et al 2011 - INITIAL RADIATION OF JAWS DEMONSTRATED STABILITY DESPITE FAUNAL AND ENVIRONMENTAL CHANGE

Summary: This paper presents a summary of the evolution of jaw morphology of gnathostomes (vertebrates with bony jaws) through time, as the agnathostomes (fish without jaws like lampreys) became less and less common. The authors scored jaws from almost 200 genera according to 31 continuous and discontinuous traits.

Compute the distance matrix: We will use “vegdist()” but it is also possible to use “dist()”.

#install the vegan package
library(vegan)
## Loading required package: permute
## Loading required package: lattice
## This is vegan 2.2-1
fish_matrix<-vegdist(fish_scale, method="euclidean", na.rm=TRUE) #set it to na.rm=TRUE because the NMDS will not take NA values
any(is.na(fish_matrix)) #optional: make sure no NA values are left
## [1] FALSE

Non-metric multidimentional scaling : the number of dimensions or axes (k) was mentionned in the paper, but it is also possible to run the test without a k value. Remember: NMDS is based on rank orders, which is why discrete and continuous traits can both be used.

meta<-metaMDS(fish_matrix, k=11) #give it a little time...

Shepard’s diagram: shows scatter around the regression between the final configuration and the original dissimilarities in the data. NMDS1 is represented on the y axis.

meta$stress #a stress around 0.05 is considered an excellent representation of the dimensions. A stress above 0.3 is typically considered suspicious. 
## [1] 0.05562442
stressplot(meta)

Plots: in plots, scale is arbitrary and so are the axes. A PCA can be used on the axes to show maximum variation.

Ggplot it!

library(ggplot2)
ggfish<- ggplot(transform(fish_scores, strat=factor(strat, levels=c("Silurian", "Lockhovian", "Pragian", "Emsian", "Eifelian", "Givetian", "Frasnian", "Famennian")))) + geom_point(data=fish_scores, aes(x=NMDS1, y=NMDS2, shape=group, fill=group, colour=group), size=4) + theme_bw() + scale_color_manual(labels = c("Acanthodii", "Actinopterygii", "Chondrichthyes",  "Placodermi","Sarcopterygii"), values= rep("white", 5)) + scale_x_continuous(limits=c(-7,9)) + scale_y_reverse(limits=c(10,-8)) + scale_shape_manual(labels = c("Acanthodii", "Actinopterygii", "Chondrichthyes",  "Placodermi","Sarcopterygii"), values = c(21, 22, 23, 24, 25)) + scale_fill_manual(labels = c("Acanthodii", "Actinopterygii", "Chondrichthyes",  "Placodermi","Sarcopterygii"), values=c("orange", "red", "yellow", "darkblue", "chartreuse3")) + theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), strip.background = element_rect(fill="white")) + geom_hline(x=0, linetype="dashed", color="grey") + geom_vline(y=0, linetype="dashed", color="grey") + xlab("Coordinate axis 1") + ylab("Coordinate axis 2")+ facet_wrap (~strat)
ggfish

Figure S9 : CA1 and CA3, with convex hulls

#gather the data to form the hulls
library(dplyr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## 
## The following object is masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter
## 
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
fish_hull<- select(fish_scores, NMDS1, NMDS2, group)
hullAca <- fish_scores[fish_scores$group=="Acanthodii",] %>%
  select(NMDS1, NMDS3)
hullAct <- fish_scores[fish_scores$group=="Actinopterygii",] %>%
  select(NMDS1, NMDS3)
hullCho <- fish_scores[fish_scores$group=="Chondrichthyes",] %>%
  select(NMDS1, NMDS3)
hullPla <- fish_scores[fish_scores$group=="Placodermi",] %>%
  select(NMDS1, NMDS3)
hullSar <- fish_scores[fish_scores$group=="Sarcopterygii",] %>%
  select(NMDS1, NMDS3)

#plot the hulls first 
fish_prehull<- ggplot() + geom_polygon(inherit.aes=F, data=hullAca[chull(hullAca),], aes(x=NMDS1, y=NMDS3), alpha=0.5, fill="orange", linetype=1, color="orange") + geom_polygon(inherit.aes=F, data=hullAct[chull(hullAct),], aes(x=NMDS1, y=NMDS3), alpha=0.5, fill="red", linetype=1, color="red") + geom_polygon(inherit.aes=F, data=hullCho[chull(hullCho),], aes(x=NMDS1, y=NMDS3), alpha=0.5, fill="yellow", linetype=1, color="yellow") + geom_polygon(inherit.aes=F, data=hullPla[chull(hullPla),], aes(x=NMDS1, y=NMDS3), alpha=0.5, fill="blue", linetype=1, color="darkblue") + geom_polygon(inherit.aes=F, data=hullSar[chull(hullSar),], aes(x=NMDS1, y=NMDS3), alpha=0.5, fill="green", linetype=1, color="chartreuse3") 
fish_prehull

final_fish<- fish_prehull + geom_point(data=fish_scores, aes(x=NMDS1, y=NMDS3, shape=group, fill=group, colour=group), size=4) + theme_bw() + scale_color_manual(labels = c("Acanthodii", "Actinopterygii", "Chondrichthyes",  "Placodermi","Sarcopterygii"), values= rep("white", 5)) + scale_x_continuous(limits=c(-7,9)) + scale_y_reverse(limits=c(9,-4)) + scale_shape_manual(labels = c("Acanthodii", "Actinopterygii", "Chondrichthyes",  "Placodermi","Sarcopterygii"), values = c(21, 22, 23, 24, 25)) + scale_fill_manual(labels = c("Acanthodii", "Actinopterygii", "Chondrichthyes",  "Placodermi","Sarcopterygii"), values=c("orange", "red", "yellow", "darkblue", "chartreuse3")) + theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), strip.background = element_rect(fill="white")) + xlab("Coordinate axis 1") + ylab("Coordinate axis 3") + geom_hline(x=0, linetype="dashed", color="grey") + geom_vline(y=0, linetype="dashed", color="grey")
final_fish

Conclusion: Although the gnathostomes became more taxonomically diverse, their jaws morphology remains relatively stable through time and cannot be linked to the rarification of the agnathostomes during the Emsian. Overall, there is very little innovation and diversification within this group.
